  <h2>How Microchipping Works</h2>
  <p>
    A microchip is a tiny passive transponder — roughly the size of a grain of rice — that is injected just under the skin between your pet's shoulder blades. The procedure is quick, similar in sensation to a routine vaccination, and requires no anesthesia.
  </p>
  <p>
    The chip contains a unique ID number that can be read by any standard scanner. When a lost pet is brought to a shelter or veterinary clinic, staff scan for a chip and use that number to look up the registered owner in a national pet recovery database.
  </p>

  <h2>When You Should Consider Microchipping</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Before traveling</strong> — especially across state lines or internationally, where microchips may be required or helpful at borders</li>
    <li><strong>For outdoor pets</strong> — cats or dogs who spend time outside face a higher risk of getting lost or disoriented</li>
    <li><strong>After adoption</strong> — update the registration to your name immediately after adopting a new pet</li>
    <li><strong>At any age</strong> — puppies, kittens, and senior pets all benefit from permanent identification</li>
    <li><strong>As a backup to tags</strong> — collars and tags can fall off; a microchip can't be removed or lost</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Happens After Microchipping</h2>
  <p>
    The chip itself does nothing until scanned. The key step after implantation is registering the chip number in a national database with your current contact information. We'll help you through this process at your visit.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remember to update your contact information in the registry any time you move or change phone numbers — an unregistered or outdated chip significantly reduces the odds of a successful reunion.
  </p>

  <h2>Is It Safe?</h2>
  <p>
    Microchips have been used safely in pets for decades. The procedure is fast and minimally uncomfortable. The chip is biocompatible and designed to stay in place permanently, causing no ongoing irritation or side effects for the vast majority of animals.
  </p>

